        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 6-month-old male infant is brought by his parents to a primary healthcare center in a semi-urban area of India. The parents are concerned about their child&#39;s lack of response to stimuli and inability to support his head, which they noticed was significantly different from their older child at this age. They also mention that the infant has had episodes described as &quot;startles&quot; that seemed abnormal and unlike typical infant reflexes. On physical examination, the physician notes the infant&#39;s peculiar hair, which is sparse, kinky, and depigmented, along with loose skin folds, microcephaly, and a pronounced forehead. Given these findings and considering the rural Indian healthcare setting where genetic testing facilities are rare, the physician recalls a rare disease of copper metabolism linked to the ATP7A gene mutation. What is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/02/picture11_ZaSc03U.jpg\" style=\"height:387px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8240295",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33071,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Menkes disease </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>mutation in the ATP7A gene</strong>, which is responsible for the <strong>transport of copper throughout the body</strong>. This mutation disrupts the normal distribution of copper, leading to a <strong>deficiency of copper</strong> in some tissues and an accumulation of copper in others.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Clinical Features;</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Developmental delay or regression</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Hypotonia (low muscle tone)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Seizures</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Abnormal hair growth and texture, including sparse, coarse, and/or kinky hair</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Skin laxity (loose folds of skin)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Small head circumference (microcephaly) or abnormal head shape (e.g., prominent forehead)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Gastrointestinal problems, such as diarrhea or vomiting</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Joint laxity or hypermobility</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Diagnosis-</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> to assess <strong>copper levels</strong> and genetic testing to identify mutations in the <strong>ATP7A gene.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Treatment</strong> options for<strong> Menkes disease </strong>are l<strong>imited</strong>, and focus primarily on <strong>managing symptoms</strong>. These may include<strong> copper replacement therapy </strong>(usually given intravenously).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Wilson&rsquo;s disease (A) </strong>involves a different gene <strong>(ATP7B)&nbsp;</strong>and typically presents later in childhood or adolescence with<strong> liver disease and neuropsychiatric symptoms.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Dubin-Johnson syndrome (C) and Rotor syndrome (D) are both hereditary hyperbilirubinemia syndromes</strong>, primarily affecting the liver, and do not present with the neurological or connective tissue features seen in Menkes disease.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Menkes disease, also known as kinky hair disease</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">, is a rare <strong>X-linked recessive disorder</strong> characterized by defective copper transport due to mutations in the <strong>ATP7A gene</strong>. This leads to a deficiency in copper-dependent enzymes like <strong>lysyl oxidase</strong> that are <strong>crucial for neurodevelopment, connective tissue formation, and hair pigmentation</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref: </span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> edition page 3123</span></strong></span></span></p>",
