      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 4-month-old infant is brought to the paediatric clinic by a concerned mother who reports that her child is not gaining weight adequately, has thin extremities, and appears shorter than expected for his age. Physical examination reveals a protruding abdomen. The child's medical history includes recurrent infections. Laboratory tests show hypoglycemia, lactic acidosis, hyperuricemia, and neutropenia. Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings, what is the most likely diagnosis, and which enzyme is defective or deficient in this condition?</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/02/picture15_djiFI6a.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"268\"></span></p>",
