        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Type1b GSD and glucose 6 phosphate translocase</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Von gierke disease</strong>/<strong>1a</strong>-due to defect in <strong>glucose 6 phosphatase.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Clinical features:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Doll like facies (fat cheeks)</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Relatively thin extremities</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Short stature</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Protruded&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; abdomen</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Diagnosis:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Laboratory finding-hypoglycemia,lactic acidosis,hyperuricemia and hyperlipidemia.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Treatment: maintain normal blood glucose (achieved by continuous nasogastric infusion of glucose or oral administration of uncooked starch)</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>TYPE 1B-All features of 1a with neutropenia (recurrent infection)</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A. Type 1a GSD and glucose-6-phosphatase:</strong> While <strong>Type 1a GSD </strong>shares many clinical and laboratory features with <strong>Type 1b, </strong>including <strong>hypoglycemia, lactic acidosis</strong>, and a <strong>protruding abdomen </strong>due to <strong>hepatomegaly</strong>, <strong>it does not typically present with neutropenia and recurrent infections.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C. Type IIIa GSD and liver and muscle glycogen debranching enzyme:</strong> <strong>Type IIIa GSD </strong>(Cori or Forbes disease) involves a <strong>deficiency in the debranching enzyme</strong>, affecting both <strong>liver and muscle</strong>, but the clinical picture is more commonly associated with myopathy and cardiomyopathy rather than neutropenia.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D: Type IV GSD and glycogen branching enzyme:</strong> <strong>Type IV GSD </strong>(Andersen's disease) is caused by a <strong>deficiency in the glycogen branching enzyme</strong>, leading to the <strong>accumulation of abnormal glycogen structure</strong>, but it is more commonly associated with progressive liver disease and does not typically present with neutropenia.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/Screenshot%202025-07-05%20180937.png\" width=\"963\" height=\"634\"></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref: </u>Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> edition, Chapter 105 â€“ Page No 3441-3446</strong></span></p>",
